ced and prominence Canadian legal practitioners and scholars, Environment in the Courtroom addresses the Canadian provinces and territories and provides context by comparison to the United States and Australia. No other collection covers these topics so comprehensively. This is an essential reference for all those interested in Canadian environmental law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental lawzCanada. 7aLAW / Environmental.2bisacsh  aAboriginal traditional knowledge and the courts.  aCanadian environmental law.  aIndigenous environmental legal traditions.  acase studies in environmental law.  acorporate environmental law.  aecosystem management law.  aenforcing environmental law.  aenvironental tribunals.  aenvironmental ethics.  aenvironmental law enforcement.  aenvironmental law.  aenvironmental prosecutions.  aenvironmental sentencing.  aevidence and environmental law.  aexpert evidence in environmental law.  ainternational environmental law.  asentencing in environmental law.  asustainability law.1 aAdams, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAffolder, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkelaitis, Andrea C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, Karina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoxall, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno, Giorilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunting, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBunting, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiasson, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, John S.G., 